5. Latest Opened Crypto ATMs in India
There is no officially published ‚Äúlatest opened ATM‚Äù list
Most recent additions (2023‚Äì2025) are:
Small-scale installations
Kiosks linked to private operators or exchanges
Often listed online but not publicly promoted
Growth is very slow due to:
RBI restrictions
Banking limitations
Taxation (30% tax + 1% TDS on crypto)

6. Cryptocurrencies Available in Indian Crypto ATMs
There is no fixed or uniform list, but based on operator history and global ATM standards:
Commonly Supported Cryptocurrencies
Bitcoin (BTC) ‚Äì Most common and primary crypto
Ethereum (ETH) ‚Äì Available on some machines
USDT (Stablecoin) ‚Äì Occasionally supported
üìå Important Notes:
Most Indian crypto ATMs are BUY-only
Selling crypto via ATM is rare
Users must usually:
Complete KYC
Link a crypto wallet
Follow operator-specific rules

7. Regulatory Status of Crypto ATMs in India
RBI has not officially approved crypto ATMs
Banks are restricted from direct crypto dealings
Crypto ATMs operate under:
Exchange partnerships
Legal ambiguity
Hence, mass adoption has not happened

8. Summary
First Crypto ATM in India: 2018, Bengaluru
Installed by: Unocoin
Current status: Very limited & unregulated
RBI approval: ‚ùå Not officially approved
Most supported crypto: Bitcoin
Adoption level: Low compared to global standards

üè¶ RBI Involvement in Crypto ATMs
RBI has not approved or regulated crypto ATMs in India.
There are no specific RBI guidelines for operating crypto ATMs.
In 2018, RBI restricted banks from dealing with crypto businesses, which led to the shutdown of India‚Äôs first crypto ATM.
In 2020, the Supreme Court lifted the banking ban, but RBI still did not authorize crypto ATMs.
RBI raises concerns about money laundering, consumer risk, and financial stability.
RBI supports Digital Rupee (CBDC) instead of private cryptocurrencies.

üáÆüá≥ Government of India (GOI) Involvement in Cryptocurrency & Crypto ATMs
1. GOI Role in Cryptocurrency
GOI has not banned cryptocurrencies, but does not recognize them as legal tender.
Cryptocurrency is treated as a Virtual Digital Asset (VDA).
GOI regulates crypto mainly through taxation and compliance laws.
30% tax on crypto profits and 1% TDS on transactions introduced in 2022.
GOI focuses on risk control, not promotion.

2. GOI Role in Crypto ATMs
GOI has not officially approved crypto ATMs.
No specific law or policy exists for crypto ATM installation.
Crypto ATMs operate under legal and regulatory uncertainty.
Any ATM dealing with cash and payments may attract scrutiny under financial and AML laws.

üìå Crypto ATMs ‚Äì Key Context 

The first crypto ATM in the world was installed in October 2013 at Vancouver, Canada, by Robocoin.
Crypto ATMs have since expanded globally and now operate in more than 65 countries.
Worldwide, there are tens of thousands of crypto ATMs, with the highest concentration in North America and Europe.
Bitcoin (BTC) is the most commonly supported cryptocurrency and is available on almost all crypto ATMs.
Other widely supported cryptocurrencies include Bitcoin Cash (BCH), Ethereum (ETH), and Litecoin (LTC).

‚úçÔ∏è Summary
Crypto ATMs were first introduced in 2013 in Vancouver, Canada. Today, they operate in over 65 countries worldwide. Major crypto ATM networks are found in countries such as the United States, Canada, Australia, Spain, and Poland. These ATMs primarily support Bitcoin, while many also offer Bitcoin Cash, Ethereum, and Litecoin.



